### Interactive Demo: Significantly Enhanced

With the full feature documentation, the demo can showcase much more without becoming overwhelming. The key is progressive depth—the visitor sees the core loop first, then can optionally explore deeper features.

**Demo Structure: Three Tabs**

The demo section has three tabs at the top:

```
[ Capture & Search ]  [ Knowledge Graph ]  [ Share & Fork ]
```

**Tab 1: Capture & Search (Default)**

This is the core demo from the initial strategy, with refinements based on the feature docs:

1. **Provider selection** — Show all 9 providers with their actual logos. Pre-select ChatGPT. When the visitor clicks "Connect," show the capture status progression from the feature docs: `capturing → processing → ready`, with the animated progress bar, spinning icon, and green checkmark.

2. **Archive view** — After import completes, show the conversations in the unified archive. Include the zone tabs from the feature docs: "All Chats | Imported | Active | Shared | Collections." Default to "Imported" to show what just arrived.

3. **View mode toggle** — In the top-right of the archive, show the four view options as icons: List, Grid, Canvas, Timeline. Default to List (most information-dense). Let the visitor click Grid to see the masonry layout. Canvas and Timeline are teasers for Tab 2.

4. **Search** — The search bar supports all four modes from the feature docs. Pre-fill with a lexical search: `"email validation regex"`. Show results with ACU-level granularity—not just conversation titles, but specific message fragments highlighted with the quality score badge. Include the composable filters panel (collapsed by default, expandable): Provider, Model, Date Range, Has Code toggle, Quality Score slider.

5. **AI Synthesis** — Below the search results, show the AI-generated summary from the feature docs: *"Across 4 conversations, you've explored email validation from 3 angles: RFC 5322 compliance, client-side UX, and backend sanitization..."*

**Tab 2: Knowledge Graph**

A dedicated view of the Canvas mode. This is the "wow" moment. Show 20-30 nodes (conversations) connected by semantic similarity edges. Nodes are:
- Sized by token count (bigger = longer conversation)
- Color-coded by provider
- Labeled with conversation titles
- Interactive: drag to reposition, hover to see details, click to expand

Include a small legend in the corner showing provider colors. The edges should have varying opacity based on similarity strength—thick, opaque edges connect highly related conversations, thin faded edges connect loosely related ones.

**Why this deserves its own tab:** The knowledge graph is the single most differentiated visual in VIVIM's product. It's the feature that makes investors lean forward. It's the screenshot that gets shared. Giving it a dedicated tab in the demo ensures every visitor sees it, but doesn't force it on visitors who just want to understand search.

**Tab 3: Share & Fork**

Demonstrate the social layer:

1. Show a conversation with an "Share" button
2. Click Share → show the three share types: Link, Circle, Direct
3. Select "Link Share" → show the granular permissions from the feature docs: `canView ✓ | canAnnotate ✓ | canRemix ○ | canReshare ○`
4. Generate a Knowledge Pulse preview: conversation overview, AI synthesis, ACU highlights
5. Show the fork action: "Fork this conversation at message #7" → a new conversation branch appears in the archive with an attribution badge showing the original author's DID

**The fork visualization is critical.** Show a small branch tree:
```
Original conversation (did:key:alice...)
  └── Your fork (starts at message #7)
       └── Your new messages continue...
```

This communicates the social layer's power without requiring explanation: conversations are forkable, attributable, and composable—like code on GitHub.

**Implementation updates:**

The three-tab demo is a single React component with tab state. Each tab lazy-loads its content. Tab 1 is ~80KB (search + mock data), Tab 2 is ~40KB (React Flow), Tab 3 is ~30KB (simpler UI). Total demo bundle: ~150KB, but only Tab 1 loads initially.

The mock data layer needs expansion:

```typescript
// Enhanced demo data structure
interface DemoConversation {
  id: string;
  provider: 'chatgpt' | 'claude' | 'gemini' | 'deepseek' | 'grok' | 'kimi' | 'mistral' | 'qwen' | 'zai';
  title: string;
  messageCount: number;
  tokenCount: number;
  model: string;
  date: string;
  status: 'ready' | 'processing';
  tags: string[];
  hasCode: boolean;
  hasMath: boolean;
  acus: DemoACU[];
  qualityScore: number;
}

interface DemoACU {
  id: string;
  content: string;
  type: 'code' | 'explanation' | 'tutorial' | 'creative' | 'analysis';
  qualityOverall: number;
  contentRichness: number;
  uniqueness: number;
  rediscoveryScore: number;
  embedding: number[]; // Pre-computed 384-dim for client-side similarity
}

// Pre-computed graph data for Tab 2
interface DemoGraphNode {
  id: string;
  conversationId: string;
  position: { x: number; y: number }; // Pre-laid-out
  provider: string;
  tokenCount: number;
  title: string;
}

interface DemoGraphEdge {
  source: string;
  target: string;
  similarity: number; // 0-1, controls opacity
}
```

For Tab 2 (Knowledge Graph), pre-compute the node positions using a force-directed layout algorithm at build time, not runtime. Store the positions in the demo data file. This means the graph renders instantly without the layout "settling" animation that React Flow's default force simulation creates. The graph appears fully formed—which is the right visual metaphor (VIVIM organizes your knowledge, it doesn't make you watch it organize).

